<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900802-0031</DOCNO><DOCID>900802-0031.</DOCID><HL>   Steel Operations Halt   As 16,000 Start Strike   At 2 Canadian Plants</HL><DATE>08/02/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LABOR STE.A CANDA T.DFS</CO><IN>STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)</IN><LP>   TORONTO -- Operations were halted yesterday at two ofCanada's largest steel producers as about 16,000 unionmembers began striking following a breakdown of contracttalks.   The shutdowns at Stelco Inc. and Algoma Steel Corp., asubsidiary of Dofasco Inc., come as Canada's steel industryis under pressure from a slowing domestic economy andincreased penetration of the Canadian market by U.S.steelmakers.</LP><TEXT>   Leo Gerard, director of District Six of the UnitedSteelworkers of America, said the union, which representsabout 10,000 workers at Toronto-based Stelco, rejected whatthe company has called its final contract offer, proposingwage increases of about 2.5% in each year of a three-yearpact. The union is seeking a higher wage settlement andbetter protection against inflation for workers andpensioners.   At Algoma, where the union represents about 6,000 workers,monetary issues haven't been broached, Mr. Gerard said. Talkswith the Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario-based company broke downover language concerning the contracting-out of work.   Officials at both companies said an orderly shutdown ofoperations had been underway for several days in anticipationof a strike. Fred Telmer, president of Stelco's steeldivision, said inventory stockpiles have been transferred tocustomers. Mr. Telmer added, &quot;We're in a closed mode.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>